    <!-- LIQUID VS GUMMY -->
    <h2 id="liquid-vs-gummy">Liquid ACV vs ACV Gummies: Which Is Better for Weight Loss?</h2>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item">
        <span class="vs-item-label">Higher Dose, Lower Cost</span>
        <h4>Liquid Apple Cider Vinegar</h4>
        <div class="vs-dose">15-30mL daily</div>
        <p>Provides 750-1500mg acetic acid per tablespoon — the clinically studied dose. Costs $0.03-$0.05 per serving. However, liquid ACV erodes tooth enamel, burns esophageal tissue, tastes harsh, and causes nausea in many users. Must be diluted in water before consumption.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item vs-best">
        <span class="vs-item-label">Safer, Better Compliance</span>
        <h4>ACV Gummies</h4>
        <div class="vs-dose">500-1000mg ACV</div>
        <p>No risk to teeth or esophagus. Pleasant taste drives daily compliance. Convenient portable format. Trade-off: lower acetic acid per serving (250-500mg vs 750-1500mg in liquid), added sugar (2-4g), and higher cost ($0.15-$0.67 per serving). Best for long-term consistent use.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <div class="tip-box-ico"><Icon name="tip" size={18} /></div>
